# Quick start - For miners.

https://github.com/tplr-ai/basilica/blob/main/docs/miner.md

TL;DR;
prerequisites:
- get a box for the miners, doesn't need to be GPU, just healthy network see https://github.com/tplr-ai/basilica/blob/main/min_compute.yml
- get an NVIDIA GPU box, either h100, h200 or b200 (you can run multiple if need to) - these boxes we call them executors
- make sure your boxes are NVDIA CUDA drivers >12.8
- make sure you register in the subnet with your miner wallet

Simple flow:
1. build the binaries
  - `./script/miner/build.sh` - https://github.com/tplr-ai/basilica/blob/main/scripts/miner/build.sh
  - `./scripts/executor/build.sh` - https://github.com/tplr-ai/basilica/blob/main/scripts/executor/build.sh
2. edit the configs (miner.correct.toml and executor.correct.toml) https://github.com/tplr-ai/basilica/tree/main/config
3. rsync the binaries, config and miner wallet to the servers, rename the config as miner.toml and executor.toml
4. run first the executors (with sudo)
  - `sudo ./basilica-executor --server --config config/executor.toml`
5. run after the miner (with sudo)
  - `sudo ./basilica-miner --config config/miner.toml`

you should be able to see the miner to send health heartbeats to your executor when the miner starts. Then wait for about 2hrs to be discovered.

if you like bash, we also have: https://github.com/tplr-ai/basilica/blob/main/scripts/deploy.sh
```
# Deploy only miner with wallet sync
./scripts/deploy.sh -s miner -m foo@1.2.3.4 -w

# Deploy only executor
./scripts/deploy.sh -s executor -e bar@4.5.6.7
```

check the network here: https://basilica-grafana.tplr.ai/

messages.content: Started a thread.

Ok team, here's the gist of the situation and what was done to rectify it.

About 2 hrs ago we received the support requests from @utortt and @.ca about the odd behaviour. So far we believed that an old exploit was trying to be taking place again, whereby a miner can hijack the executors of another miner, but we knew  we had sufficient defence around it.

After further investigation, we saw that it was actually a new exploit, whereby an attacker can double-register the axon and impersonate another miner. So far we believed (but never tested) that wasn't possible as the protocol would prevent a duplication of an axon registration, but we're proven wrong.

in detail

```
miner_uid=111 --> registers with 1.1.1.1:8080 - real miner
miner_uid=222 --> registers with 1.1.1.1:8080 - fraud miner
validator --eval--> miner_uid=222
validator --connect--> 1.1.1.1:8080 - OK
validator --eval--> miner_uid=111
validator --connect--> 1.1.1.1:8080 - NOT OK, duplication of hardware
```

There was a race condition, whereby in the case that the validator was evaluating the miner `222` first, the ownership of the executors was assigned to `miner_uid=222`.

The solution that this PR proposes fixes the matter in 3 ways:

- The miner receives the hotkey the validator is indenting to eval, if it doesn't match, the miner service will reject (cause the `miner_uid=222` to fail eval)
```
validator --eval--> miner_uid=222
validator --connect--> 1.1.1.1:8080 - NOT OK - my UID is 111
```

- the validator checks that the return signature is also from the intended miner, this will prevent proxy attacks
```
validator --eval--> miner_uid=222
validator --connect--> <proxy> --> 1.1.1.1:8080 - NOT OK - my UID is 111
```

- the validator and miner checks whether the nonce in the signature is fresh to prevent replay attacks.

ok this is code complete. I'll spend some more time testing it. but here's the gist

- A100 for 80GB support
- `min_gpu_count` and `min_gpu_vram` are introduced as filters for emissions
- H200 is deprecated in favour of A100 80GB
- B200 minimum count is 8

config looks like this:

```toml
[emission.gpu_allocations]
A100 = { weight = 8.0, min_gpu_count = 1, min_gpu_vram = 80 }
H100 = { weight = 12.0, min_gpu_count = 1, min_gpu_vram = 80 }
B200 = { weight = 80.0, min_gpu_count = 8, min_gpu_vram = 192 }
```
